          {
            "type": "message",
            "id": "msg_4b205924b8394b730069a88b1e6a2081909c813452755ef3d6",
            "created_by": {
              "response_id": "resp_4b205924b8394b730069a88b16ce388190a543965fc8094f38"
            },
            "response_id": "resp_4b205924b8394b730069a88b16ce388190a543965fc8094f38",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Foundry Agent Service is Microsoft’s managed runtime for building and operating AI “agents” in Microsoft Foundry—moving beyond simple chatbots toward production automation (for example: summarizing documents, processing invoices, handling support tickets, or executing multi-step workflows). It’s designed to help you go from prototype to production by providing orchestration, safety, and enterprise integrations out of the box.【5:0†source】\n\n## What it does (in practical terms)\n- **Runs and manages agent conversations**: maintains the agent’s conversation state and manages how messages/threads/runs are handled.【5:0†source】\n- **Orchestrates tool use**: the model can decide when to call tools (search, retrieval, actions) based on the user request and context, then incorporate tool results into its response.【5:0†source】【5:1†source】\n- **Enforces safety and policies**: includes built-in content safety and “trust by design” controls so agents are more usable in real business scenarios.【5:0†source】\n- **Connects to enterprise foundations**: integrates with identity, networking, and observability so you can deploy securely and monitor behavior in production.【5:0†source】\n\n## How “agents” are viewed in Foundry\nFoundry frames agents as **composable units**: an agent has a role, is powered by a selected model, and is equipped with specific tools. Agents can act independently or as part of workflows involving other agents or humans.【5:0†source】\n\n## Tools: how agents get knowledge and take actions\nFoundry Agent Service supports a range of built-in and integration tools, typically grouped as:【5:1†source】\n\n**Knowledge tools (to ground responses in data)**\n- Examples include **Azure AI Search**, **File Search**, **Microsoft Fabric**, and web grounding/search tools.【5:1†source】\n\n**Action tools (to do things)**\n- Examples include **Azure Logic Apps**, **OpenAPI spec-based tools**, **MCP (Model Context Protocol) endpoints**, **function calling**, **Azure Functions**, and **browser automation** (for web tasks).【5:1†source】\n\nThe key idea: tools are optional capabilities you attach, and the model chooses which to call during a run based on intent (e.g., web search for real-time info).【5:1†source】\n\n## Web grounding/search options (important distinction)\nFoundry includes ways to let agents use public web data:\n- **Grounding with Bing Search (classic)**: can pull real-time public web info; responses include citations/links that must be displayed per Microsoft’s requirements.【5:3†source】\n- **Grounding with Bing Custom Search (classic)**: lets you restrict web searching to a configurable set of domains/subdomains (useful for “only search our approved sites”). It has specific data transfer/compliance notes and can incur costs.【5:2†source】\n\n## What would you like to do with it?\nIf you tell me your scenario (internal knowledge base Q&A, ticket automation, data entry/invoice processing, website actions, etc.) and whether you’re using the **new Agents API** or **classic**, I can outline the recommended architecture (models + tools + safety/observability) and the minimal steps to implement it.",
